-----------
Basic HTML
-----------

1. What is HTML, and what is its purpose?
=>
- HTML (Hyper Text Markup Language) is the standard language for creating web pages. It defines the structure and content of a web page.
- Its purpose is to provide a framework for organizing text, images, videos, and other elements on a webpage.

-----------

2. Explain the difference between elements, tags, and attributes in HTML.
=>
- Elements: These are the building blocks of an HTML document. They consist of opening and closing tags, and they can contain content or other elements.
- Tags: These are used to define elements. They are enclosed in angle brackets (<>). For example, <p> and </p> define a paragraph.
- Attributes: These are used to provide additional information about elements. They are placed within the opening tag and have a name-value pair format. For example, <img src="image.jpg"> uses the src attribute to specify the image source.

----------

3. What are the different types of HTML elements?
=>
- Structural Elements: These define the overall structure of a webpage, such as <html>, <head>, and <body>.
- Text Elements: These are used to represent text, such as <p>, <h1>, <h2>, etc.
- List Elements: These are used to create lists, such as <ul> (unordered list) and <ol> (ordered list).
- Table Elements: These are used to create tables, such as <table>, <tr>, and <td>.
- Form Elements: These are used to create forms for user input, such as <form>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea>.
- Image and Multimedia Elements: These are used to embed images, audio, and video content, such as <img>, <audio>, and <video>.

----------
HTML Structure and Semantics -
----------

4. Explain the basic structure of an HTML document.
=>
HTML

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>My Web Page</title>
</head>
<body>
  </body>
</html>

- <!DOCTYPE html>: This declaration specifies the document type as HTML5.
- <html>:</html>: This is the root element of an HTML document.
- <head>:</head>: This section contains metadata about the webpage, such as the title.
- <body>:</body>: This section contains the visible content of the webpage.

---------

5. What is the importance of semantic HTML?
=>
- Semantic HTML uses elements that accurately describe their content, making the webpage more understandable for both humans and search engines.
- It improves accessibility for users with disabilities and helps with search engine optimization (SEO).

----------
HTML Styling and Formatting -
----------

6. How can you style HTML elements using CSS?
=> 
- You can use CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) to apply styles to HTML elements. CSS rules are typically placed in a separate .css file or within the <head> section of the HTML document.

---------

7. Explain the concept of inline, block, and inline-block elements.

- Inline elements: These elements do not start on a new line and do not allow other elements to wrap around them. Examples include <span>, <em>, and <a>.
- Block elements: These elements start on a new line and allow other elements to wrap around them. Examples include <p>, <h1>, and <div>.
- Inline-block elements: These elements combine the characteristics of inline and block elements. They do not start on a new line but allow other elements to wrap around them. Examples include <img> and <input>.

----------
Advanced HTML Topics -
----------

8. What is the purpose of the <iframe> element?
=>
- The <iframe> element is used to embed a webpage within another webpage. This allows you to display content from another website on your page.

---------

9. Explain the difference between HTML5 and previous versions of HTML.
=>
HTML5 introduced several new features and improvements, such as:
 - New semantic elements: <header>, <nav>, <main>, <article>, <section>, <aside>, <footer>, <figure>, and <figcaption>.
 - Canvas and SVG: For creating graphics and animations.
 - Video and audio elements: For embedding multimedia content.
 - Local storage: For storing data locally on the user's device.
 - Web workers: For running JavaScript code in the background.

---------

10. What are HTML forms used for, and what are some common form elements?
=>
HTML forms are used to collect user input. Common form elements include:
 - <input>: Can be used for various types of input, such as text, checkboxes, radio buttons, and file uploads.
 - <select>: Creates a dropdown list.
 - <textarea>: Creates a multi-line text input.
 - <button>: Creates a button for submitting or resetting the form.


